  "base_commit": "86be28eb85bfac05f160a8104515d0033c3e8409",
  "pr_number": 1770,
  "issue_number": 1764,
  "issue_title": "A villainous-choice \"you \u2026\" branch resolves against the player who made the choice instead of the source's controller (CR 701.55a / CR 109.5)",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nWhen a player resolves a \"choose one or more\"/villainous-choice effect, `crate::game::effects::choose_one_of::resolve_branch` binds the chosen branch's *scoped player* to the **chooser** and then resolves the branch:\n\n```rust\n// crates/engine/src/game/effects/choose_one_of.rs:135-145\nlet mut resolved = build_resolved_from_def(branch, source_id, controller);\nresolved.context = context;\nresolved.targets = parent_targets;\nresolved.set_scoped_player_recursive(player);   // player = the CHOOSER\nif !resolved.targets.iter().any(|t| matches!(t, TargetRef::Player(pid) if *pid == player)) {\n    resolved.targets.push(TargetRef::Player(player));\n}\n```\n\n`set_scoped_player_recursive(player)` sets `ability.scoped_player = Some(chooser)`. But the player-reference resolver reads `scoped_player` for **both** \"that player\" *and* \"you\":\n\n```rust\n// crates/engine/src/game/targeting.rs:674\nTargetFilter::Controller => Some(ability.scoped_player.unwrap_or(ability.controller)),\n// ...\nTargetFilter::ScopedPlayer => ability.scoped_player,\n```\n\nSo every `TargetFilter::Controller` reference in the chosen branch \u2014 i.e. every \"you\"/\"your\" instruction (CR 109.5) \u2014 resolves to the **chooser**, not to the source's controller. In a villainous choice the chooser is an opponent, so a \"you do something good\" branch is performed by/for the opponent who was given the choice.\n\nThis is only invisible in ordinary modal spells, where the chooser *is* the controller. CR 701.55a makes the two players deliberately different.\n\n## Failure mode (concrete example)\n\n**Dr. Eggman, the Mad Scientist** \u2014 \"\u2026each opponent faces a villainous choice \u2014 **That player discards a card**, or **you may put a Construct, Robot, or Vehicle card from your hand onto the battlefield**.\" (Present in the parser suite at `crates/engine/src/parser/oracle_effect/...` Eggman test.)\n\n- Branch A, \"That player discards a card\", parses to a `ScopedPlayer` subject \u2192 correctly resolves to the opponent.\n- Branch B, \"**you** may put a card from **your hand** onto the battlefield\", parses to `TargetFilter::Controller` (the parser maps \"you\"/\"your\" to `Controller`).\n\nThe opponent is the chooser. If the opponent picks Branch B, `set_scoped_player_recursive(opponent)` makes `TargetFilter::Controller` resolve to the opponent (via `scoped_player.unwrap_or(...)`). The engine then has **the opponent put a card from the opponent's own hand onto the battlefield** \u2014 when the card means *Dr. Eggman's controller* puts a card from *their* hand.\n\nDownstream effects:\n\n- Every villainous-choice card whose options contrast \"that player \u2026\" with \"you \u2026\" is affected (e.g. \"they lose 3 life, or you draw a card\" templates): the beneficial \"you\" branch acts on the wrong player.\n- Any \"you\"/\"your\"-scoped sub-instruction inside the chosen branch (draw, gain life, put onto battlefield, search your library, etc.) is attributed to the chooser, not the controller.\n\nThis is analogous to how the engine already distinguishes a fixed controller from rebound scope with `TargetFilter::OriginalController` (`targeting.rs:677`), which resolves to `original_controller` and deliberately ignores `scoped_player` \"even when player_scope iteration has rebound the controller.\" Villainous-choice \"you\" references need that same fixed-controller anchoring.\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Resolve a villainous-choice effect (`Effect::ChooseOneOf`) whose chooser scope is the opponent(s) and one branch's subject is \"you\" (e.g. Dr. Eggman's activated ability).\n2. Have the opponent (chooser) select the \"you \u2026\" branch.\n3. Observe that the branch's `Controller`/\"you\" instructions act on the opponent (chooser) \u2014 e.g. a card is put onto the battlefield from the opponent's hand \u2014 instead of the source's controller.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nThe chooser performs the *act of choosing* (CR 701.55a), but the actions inside the chosen option are performed by the player the option's text names: \"that player\" \u2192 the chooser, and \"you\" \u2192 the source's controller (CR 109.5). A \"you put a card from your hand onto the battlefield\" branch must put a card from the **controller's** hand.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\nThe branch's scoped player is set to the chooser, and `TargetFilter::Controller` reads `scoped_player`, so every \"you\" reference in the chosen branch resolves to the chooser. The controller's \"you\" benefit is applied to the opponent instead.\n\n## Suggested fix\n\nDecouple the branch's \"you\"/`Controller` references from the chooser-bound `scoped_player`, keeping \"that player\"/`ScopedPlayer` bound to the chooser. Reuse the existing fixed-controller mechanism:\n\n- In `resolve_branch`, bind the chooser as `scoped_player` (as today, for `ScopedPlayer`), but also anchor the source controller with `resolved.original_controller = Some(controller)` and rewrite the chosen branch's `TargetFilter::Controller` player-references to `TargetFilter::OriginalController` before resolution (a small recursive remap over the branch's effect/filter tree). `OriginalController` already resolves independently of `scoped_player` (`targeting.rs:677`), so \"you\" then resolves to the controller while \"that player\" still resolves to the chooser.\n- Equivalently, gate the `scoped_player` binding so it never shadows `Controller` for a villainous branch (e.g., resolve \"you\" via `original_controller`).\n- Add a regression test (in a test module outside `choose_one_of.rs`, which has no inline tests): an opponent-facing villainous choice where the opponent selects a \"you draw a card / you put a card from your hand\" branch must apply that action to the **controller**, not the chooser.",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-01T19:38:53.000Z",
